[2]
Date: Mon 17 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters AlertNet, Mon 17 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/ISL118954.htm>


Pakistan: Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever outbreak confirmed
------------------------------------------------------------
QUETTA: Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever has killed 4 people and infected
at least 6 more in Pakistan, health officials said on Monday. Tariq Khoso,
medical superintendent at Fatima Jinnah Chest Hospital in the south western
city of Quetta, said 6 patients suffering from the fever had been admitted
and placed in an isolation ward. "They arrived at the hospital in the past
week from 2 affected regions," Khoso told Reuters in the city, capital of
Baluchistan province bordering Afghanistan. "We have sent medical teams to
the affected area of Qila Saifullah and adjoining Islambagh to monitor the
situation there," Baluchistan province's director general for health, Pir
Mohammad Khawajakhel, told Reuters.

A World Health Organization official confirmed that the disease had killed
4 people but said there was no immediate threat of an outbreak as doctors
were monitoring the situation. Health officials say more than 300 cases of
the disease have been recorded in Pakistan since 2001 and of those 38
people have died including some doctors, nurses and surgeons.

